While I respect your right to an opinion and I won't call you a Disney shill, I really do struggle to see how any genuine Star Wars fan could call The Rise of Skywalker amazing. While it was very clear that JJ tried to make amends after the shit show that was TLJ, the execution was extremely poor.

I actually laughed out loud in the cinema when Palpatine died. How can your force lightening be so powerful as to nullify an entire star fleet but not be powerful enough to get past a lightsaber?

Anyway, there are dozens of glaring plot holes, terrible edits, and laughable 'serious' moments, but the bottom line is that it was impossible to care about it all. How could you care about Rey as a character when there was zero character development throughout the 3 movies? How could you care about the relationship between Kylo and his parents when we never saw them together as a family? How could you care about the return of Palpatine when it wasn't even explained how he survived? How could you care about his next big plan or his motives when the story didn't even bother exploring it? How could you care about any of the legacy characters when they were just shamelessly used for nostalgia?

The Rise of Skywalker was definitely a big fu*k you to The Last Jedi, but Disney's Star Wars sequels were a big fu*k you to the fans.

But at least one person enjoyed it. Good for you.

snippet.textDisplay: Her calling herself a Skywalker was bit weak but I think they were trying to prove a point. Palpatine was in her blood. Leia knew it from the beginning. But Leía saw the light in her and constantly reminded her to not fear who she was. She took her in as her own and in the end Palpatine was defeated and completely erased from history when she took on a new name. Also, Luke and Leía showed their approval and it was almost like the film was trying to teach the point that you don’t have to be what your parents were. You can make your own choices and your true family is the one that treats you as such; true family can define you. Adoptive parents can be more than your flesh and blood. I think that was the moral of the story they tried to highlight. I will say however, I think it would have been better if they did not kill off Ben and instead they married. This would truly make her a Skywalker in totality and it would also have eliminated the Palpatine name from history directly from the bloodline of Skywalker. It would have been accomplished the balance in the name of love instead of hate, the rejecting of the dark side by means of the light. It would open the door to a new ideology when it comes to the strict rules and traditions of the Jedi of old. It would also have made their awkward and almost completely uncalled for kiss more tolerable. It would have made that relationship more realistic and a happier ending for the Skywalker’s as a whole. In the end they did the best they could given the conditions of the story and where they left off in the previous films. I think it was handled well and we can’t cry over what can’t be changed.

I liked the movie too. I have some problems with it, but it's the best in this trilogy. Though I disagree with you saying that you don't need to see The Last Jedi to watch this film.
If you skip The Last Jedi you'll be confused as to why Snoke isn't around anymore, why Luke is a force ghost, how Rey and Kylo are having those force Skype calls, why Hux hates Kylo and a handful of other minor things.
And though a lot of people are saying this movie retcons The Last Jedi, I have to disagree with that too. It's not a very smooth transition but it does follow through with what The Last Jedi set up. Luke catching the lightsaber isn't just simply a jab at The Last Jedi, because in that film Luke went through his character arc of having given up, to realising he was wrong and helping the Resistance. Luke catching the lightsaber follows naturally. Palpatine being behind Snoke and what Kylo thought to be Vader's voice is also a logical follow-up from Snoke's character being killed off so simply. Though I wish the final force Skype call between Rey and Kylo at the end of The Last Jedi was caused by Palpatine (as Snoke said he connected them all those times prior). Rey being a Palpatine helps explain why she's a Mary Sue, but doesn't fix the problem entirely. And Rey's parents being "nobody" never sat well with me. I'm glad the film was set quite some time after The Last Jedi and it shows her training at the start, though it does feel a bit like it's too little too late.

Let's not forget that people love the original trilogy but there's plenty of "retconning" in that too. All the stuff about Darth Vader being Luke's father despite Obi Wan saying that Vader killed Luke's father, and then the whole "from a certain point of view" talk to explain it all. And Leia saying "somehow I always knew" about being Luke's sister despite having passionately kissed him on the lips in the previous film.

If you're angry at Rise of Skywalker for "retconning" then you should be equally angry at Empire Strikes Back and Return of the Jedi.
